<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-541-212  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 541 212.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  June 4 1990 v4 n22 p49(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Philcox guides IRS' modernization. (IRS CIO tries to avoid wrongturn in automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Danca, Richard A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Internal Revenue Service (IRS) CIO, Henry H. Philcox, discussesautomation and upgrading practices at the agency.andP;  The IRSpresently is working on a project called the Tax ModernizationSystem program.andP;  As this new system moves forward, the othersystems presently running will have to work without majorproblems.andP;  Each step of the newly automated system implementationis carefully planned to avoid data integrity problems.andP;  Thebiggest obstacle is an acquisition process that is tightlyregulated and restricted.andP;  The size of the IRS data base isenormous with 19 terabytes of information at any given moment asinventory; there are 1.2 terabytes of ASCII data and 18 terabytesof images.andP;  These figures encompass tax data only, they do notinclude administrative data.andP;  IRS employees deal with 40 millionrequisitions each year for specific individual pieces of paper.andO;Electronic imaging will make it possible for several IRS agents toview a document simultaneously, thus avoiding the panic when asingle piece of paper is lost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Office AutomationImaging TechnologyDocument Management SystemsGovernment AgencyUnited States. Internal Revenue Service.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Henry H. Philcox. (portrait)Person:    Philcox, Henry H. (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>